    "summary": "The World Trade Organization was established on January 1, 1995, replacing the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), which had governed international trade rules since 1947. The WTO provided a permanent institutional framework for negotiating trade agreements, resolving disputes between member states, and monitoring national trade policies. Its creation marked the culmination of the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade negotiations, which had lasted nearly eight years.\n\nThe organization introduced a binding dispute settlement mechanism that gave teeth to international trade rules, allowing countries to bring complaints against trading partners and receive rulings backed by authorized retaliation. By the end of the twentieth century, the WTO had over 140 member states accounting for the vast majority of global trade. Its founding reflected the post-Cold War consensus around trade liberalization as a driver of economic development, though it also generated controversy over its effects on developing nations and domestic labor standards.",
